{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17525092","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17525092"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:12:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:12:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14054"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14054","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14054"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.19,0.49,0.02,0.25]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6708"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92628"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6708","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6708"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14054"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75969"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"687"},{"type":"tags","id":"1282"},{"type":"tags","id":"2356"},{"type":"tags","id":"2787"},{"type":"tags","id":"3004"},{"type":"tags","id":"4061"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13943"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31750"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35577"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43929"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92628","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92628"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of nausea, vomiting, and right upper quadrant pain. She admits to taking an intentional overdose of paracetamol three days ago following a relationship breakdown. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell with a pulse rate of 110/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. She is jaundiced and has mild right upper quadrant tenderness. Investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBilirubin: 120 \u00b5mol/L (3-20)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EALT: 3500 U/L (5-40)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAST: 3200 U/L (5-40)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EALP: 150 U/L (30-120)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EINR: 2.8 (0.8-1.2)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine: 150 \u00b5mol/L (45-90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EParacetamol level: 5 mg/L (\u0026lt;20)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EArterial pH: 7.32, lactate 1.8\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Arrange urgent liver biopsy","Transfer to a liver transplant centre","N-acetylcysteine infusion","Activated charcoal","Close observation and supportive care"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with acute liver failure secondary to paracetamol overdose. The most appropriate next step in management is to start an\u003Cstrong\u003E N-acetylcysteine infusion\u003C/strong\u003E. N-acetylcysteine (NAC) is the antidote for paracetamol toxicity and should be administered in all cases of paracetamol-induced acute liver failure, even if the paracetamol level is not significantly elevated at presentation. NAC helps to replenish glutathione stores, which are crucial for detoxifying the toxic metabolites of paracetamol. When patients present earlier following paracetamol ingestion without clear evidence of liver injury, a paracetamol treatment normogram can be used to determine if NAC treatment is indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering activated charcoal\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate in this case as it is only generally effective within 1-2 hours of ingestion, or up to 4 hours in cases of massive ingestion. This patient took the overdose three days ago, so activated charcoal would not be beneficial.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransfer to a liver transplant centre\u003C/strong\u003E is an important consideration in the management of acute liver failure, but it is not currently required. While involvement of a liver transplant centre will be crucial if the patient\u0027s condition worsens, starting NAC infusion is more urgent and can be initiated immediately in the Emergency Department. The King\u0027s College Criteria can be used to assess the need for liver transplantation in paracetamol-induced acute liver failure, considering factors such as arterial pH, INR, serum creatinine, and grade of encephalopathy. Patients meeting this criteria should be stabilised and transferred to a liver transplant centre urgently.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArranging urgent liver biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in this case. The diagnosis of paracetamol-induced acute liver failure is clear from the history and laboratory findings. Liver biopsy carries significant risks in the setting of coagulopathy and is rarely necessary for diagnosis or management of acute liver failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClose observation and supportive care\u003C/strong\u003E are important aspects of managing acute liver failure, but they are not the most appropriate next step in this scenario. While ongoing monitoring and supportive measures are crucial, the immediate priority is to administer the specific antidote, N-acetylcysteine, to mitigate further liver damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to starting NAC, management of this patient should include supportive care, close monitoring of mental status for signs of hepatic encephalopathy, and early involvement of intensive care and a liver transplant centre. The patient should also receive a psychiatric evaluation given the intentional nature of the overdose.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["N-acetylcysteine (NAC) is the antidote for paracetamol toxicity and should be administered in all cases of paracetamol-induced acute liver failure.","Early involvement of a liver transplant centre is an important consideration in the management of acute liver failure."],"references":["Chiew AL, Reith D, Pomerleau A, Wong A, Isoardi KZ, Soderstrom J, Buckley NA. Updated guidelines for the management of paracetamol poisoning in Australia and New Zealand. Med J Aust. 2020 Mar;212(4):175-183. Available at: https://www.mja.com.au/system/files/issues/212_04/mja250428.pdf","Cordoba J, Dhawan A, Larsen FS, Manns M, Samuel D, Simpson KJ, Yaron I; EASL Governing Board representative; Bernardi M. EASL Clinical Practical Guidelines on the management of acute (fulminant) liver failure. J Hepatol. 2017 May;66(5):1047-1081. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28417882/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75969"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14054"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75969","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75969"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-18T17:26:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-09T1